# Write a function to calculate skewness. (Skewness = ()3/(1)3)
# importing statistics to handle statistical operations

# loading massive amounts of modules for counter checks
import statistics as stats
import numpy as np
import scipy as sp

def skewness( object ):
    local_N = len(object)
    local_Mean = sum(object)/local_N
    
    # standards are the same but different
    local_Std = stats.stdev(object, local_Mean)
    local_npStd = np.std(object)
    
    skewd_Std = 0
    skewd_npStd = 0
    
    for i in range( 0, local_N, 1 ):
        skewd_Std += ( ( ( object[i]-local_Mean )**3 ) 
                            / ( ( local_N-1 ) * local_Std**3 ) )
        skewd_npStd += ( ( ( object[i]-local_Mean )**3 ) 
                            / ( ( local_N-1 ) * local_npStd**3 ) )   
        
    return local_Std, skewd_Std, local_npStd, skewd_npStd

results = skewness(ap["wkd_day_value"])

print( "Using 'statistics' gives a standard deviation of", results[0], "\n and a skewness of", results[1], ".\n" )
print( "Using 'numpy' gives a standard deviation of", results[2], "\n and a skewness of", results[3], ".\n" )
print( "And according to 'scipy' the skewness is", sp.stats.skew(ap["wkd_day_value"]), ".\n")
print( "Further analyses should reveal if the results of the different approaches\nfollow a standard distribution or are skewed. All methods agree that there's\na positive skew, though.")

===================================================================
4.
Using 'statistics' gives a standard deviation of 16.037734417099177 
 and a skewness of 1.0264905792191763 .

Using 'numpy' gives a standard deviation of 16.021089125206796 
 and a skewness of 1.0296933564962365 .

And according to 'scipy' the skewness is 1.0275570632254987 .

Further analyses should reveal if the results of the different approaches
follow a standard distribution or are skewed. All methods agree that there's
a positive skew, though.

print("Another thing to note is the difference of the distributions of values\n for each buffer size, easily visible at the axis, where for example a\n buffer of 5000 covers a range from zero up to approx. ten thousand,\n whereas the smallest buffer only ranges up to approx. three hundred.\nThat being said, the frequency distributions (plots on diagonal axis)\n for the 50 and 500 m buffer class indeed show peaks at zero for all\n urban type classes, only the 5000 m buffer diverts from this by having\n different peak values for the different urban types.\n\nSo I suggest only the four plots in the upper left can be used to derive\ncredible statements about correlations, though it is noteworthy that even\nzero values in the lower range-buffer classes go along with non-zero NO2\nvalues, so if the aim was to look at the relation between roads and\nNitrogen dioxide this suggests a certain threshold which exists indepen-\ndently from roads and another mechanism at play in the region of study.\n\nThe correlation between wkd_day_value and road_class_3_5000 appears quite\nsolid, with rural, suburban and urban types clearly separated in clusters\nand symmetrical along the diagonal (though the skew mentioned above\nshould be kept in mind here). For the other parts it would be necessary\nto decide on what to do with the zero values, but in general the 5000 m\nbuffer seems to be the best option for looking at the influence of\ntraffic on primary roads regarding greenhouse gases in this area.\n\nIt can also be seen that if one where to only look at one group, the\ncorrelation at times would be inverse to that of all groups combined,\nbeing an example for the Simpson's Paradox discussed in class.")

Another thing to note is the difference of the distributions of values
 for each buffer size, easily visible at the axis, where for example a
 buffer of 5000 covers a range from zero up to approx. ten thousand,
 whereas the smallest buffer only ranges up to approx. three hundred.
That being said, the frequency distributions (plots on diagonal axis)
 for the 50 and 500 m buffer class indeed show peaks at zero for all
 urban type classes, only the 5000 m buffer diverts from this by having
 different peak values for the different urban types.

So I suggest only the four plots in the upper left can be used to derive
credible statements about correlations, though it is noteworthy that even
zero values in the lower range-buffer classes go along with non-zero NO2
values, so if the aim was to look at the relation between roads and
Nitrogen dioxide this suggests a certain threshold which exists indepen-
dently from roads and another mechanism at play in the region of study.

The correlation between wkd_day_value and road_class_3_5000 appears quite
solid, with rural, suburban and urban types clearly separated in clusters
and symmetrical along the diagonal (though the skew mentioned above
should be kept in mind here). For the other parts it would be necessary
to decide on what to do with the zero values, but in general the 5000 m
buffer seems to be the best option for looking at the influence of
traffic on primary roads regarding greenhouse gases in this area.

It can also be seen that if one where to only look at one group, the
correlation at times would be inverse to that of all groups combined,
being an example for the Simpson's Paradox discussed in class.

Here, a positive correlation between the 500 m, 5000 m buffer classes
as well as the wkd_day_value can be observed and even with the 50 m
buffer class seems more clear.

All in all the data suggests urban roads contribute far more towards
Nitrogen dioxide emissions than the other types, which does make sense
as in urban areas more traffic lights and other possibilities for
traffic congestions exist (per area of observation), most emissions
are due to acceleration of fossil-fuel-driven vehicles.
The case between suburban and rural roads seems ambivalent, while
suburban roads are the bigger emitters it is not quite clear if sum
of rural roads outweighs the suburban types and therefore who might
be the larger contributor overall. Local roads seem to cover the area
to a larger extent than primary roads, visible from the frequencies
for both the smaller buffer sizes, at least per length - there's no
information about the widths of the roads.
